{{for|additional information|wikipedia:Mortgage-backed security}}
'''Mortgage backed securities''', which include Ginnie Mae Securities (GNMA) and Collateralized Debt Instruments (CDO), are among the most complex fixed income securities. Vanguard provides a basic description of mortgage backed securities in the prospectus to its bond funds: {{blockquote| Mortgage-backed securities represent interests in underlying pools of mortgages. Unlike ordinary bonds, which generally pay a fixed rate of interest at regular intervals and then repay principal upon maturity, mortgage-backed securities pass through both interest and principal from underlying mortgages as part of their regular payments. Because the mortgages underlying the securities can be prepaid at any time by homeowners or by corporate borrowers, mortgage-backed securities are subject to [https://www.investopedia.com/terms/p/prepaymentrisk.asp prepayment risk]. These types of securities are issued by a number of government agencies, including the GNMA, the FHLMC, and the FNMA, [as well as by private issuers]. As a rule, when interest rates rise, bond prices fall. The opposite is also true: Bond prices go up when interest rates fall. Mortgage-backed securities are different. In general, declining interest rates will not lift the prices of mortgage-backed securities—such as GNMAs—as much as the prices of comparable bonds. Why? Because when interest rates fall, the bond market tends to discount the prices of mortgage-backed securities for prepayment risk—the possibility that homeowners will refinance their mortgages at lower rates and cause the bonds to be paid off prior to maturity. In part to compensate for this prepayment possibility, mortgage-backed securities tend to offer higher yields than other bonds of comparable credit quality and maturity.}}
==Risks== In addition to the [[Bond basics#Risks | normal risks of bonds]], mortgage-backed securities exhibit negative [[Bonds: advanced topics#Convexity|convexity]]. This negative convexity results from [https://www.investopedia.com/terms/c/contractionrisk.asp contraction risk], when homeowners refinance as interest rates fall, and from [https://www.investopedia.com/terms/e/extensionrisk.asp extension risk], when homeowners delay pre-payments as interest rates rise.
Determining the exact extent of this negative convexity is impossible, as it depends on how mortgagors behave. In general, this behavior is non-linear: small changes make little difference in homeowner behavior but large changes cause homeowners to overcome inconvenience and refinance in larger numbers. Statistical modeling can approximate the extent of negative convexity, but behavior with large interest rate changes is relatively hard to predict. Bondholders are compensated for this risk by the "option-adjusted spread," which can be interpreted as the market's assessment of the size of prepayment risk.
== Role in a portfolio == While there is some question as to whether the option-adjusted spread has historically been enough to compensate investors for the increased risk of MBSs, the general consensus is that the market prices these securities efficiently. However, in [[Special:BookSources/978-0-312-35363-6|''The Only Guide to a Winning Bond Strategy You'll Ever Need'']], [[Larry Swedroe]] argues that these bonds do not properly diversify the risks of stocks in the portfolio as a whole due to their negative convexity: "In a rising rate environment ... MBS will have increasing correlation with equities, and this is not a good thing."
Other Bogleheads hold large allocations of their portfolio in MBS, either by holding Total Bond Market (since a large portion of that fund is in MBS) or directly through the [[GNMA]] fund. [[John Bogle]] has expressed some skepticism of these bonds, calling them "non-bonds."<ref>{{cite web| url=https://johncbogle.com/wordpress/2007/06/15/john-bogle-responds-to-ask-jack-questions-2/| title=John Bogle responds to “Ask Jack” questions| publisher=The Bogle eBlog| date=June 15, 2007| accessdate=October 3, 2025}}</ref>
Holding MBSs as a part of a diversified bond portfolio is unlikely to lead to ruin, and over time you are likely to be compensated for the increased risk of negative convexity with higher yield. Therefore, it can make sense to invest in MBSs, either directly or through a total bond market fund (which typically are about one-third MBS), provided you understand that you are taking a moderate amount of additional risk. If you do not want the added risk of negative convexity, or you are interested in lowering the correlation between the bond component of your portfolio and the equity component, you would be fine sticking to bonds that lack embedded options.
== Types of mortgage-backed security ==
; Government and quasi-governmental agencies : [[GNMA]] obligations are backed by the full faith and credit of the U.S. Government, just as [[Treasury Bonds | Treasuries]] are. [[Fannie Mae]] and [[Freddie Mac]] are public companies but are assumed to have the backing of the U.S. Government. This was borne out in the 2008 crisis, when the Federal Government did just that. They are therefore considered quasi-governmental agencies. ; Corporate :Non-government-backed MBSs are a very small part of the market. GNMA, Fannie Mae, and Freddie Mac hold the bulk of all MBSs.
