{{US|reason=harmful}}
Stocks may be classified by the size of the corporation. This is most commonly done looking at the [[Market capitalization| market capitalization]]. Market capitalization is simply a measurement found by taking a stock's current share price and multiplying it by the number of stock shares outstanding.
Exact market cap ranges will vary among different financial and rating institutions, but there are three different terms commonly used to describe stocks by their general size: Large Cap stocks; Mid Cap stocks; and Small Cap stocks. Market cap terms are relative and are constantly changing as companies get bigger and smaller.
{{Market cap table}}
Capitalization ranges for companies that are smaller than small cap stocks include micro cap and nano cap stocks.
{{Market cap table 2}}
==Risk and returns==
===US markets=== [[File:1-18.gif|thumb|right|400px|Figure 1, from [[William Bernstein]], [http://www.efficientfrontier.com/ef/499/inept.htm The Investment Entertainment Pricing Theory (INEPT)], ''Efficient Frontier'', 1999]]
Beginning with Rolf Banz in 1981<ref>Rolf W. Banz, "The Relationship Between Return and Market Value of Common Stocks," Journal of Financial Economics, 9 (1981), pp. 3-18 </ref> and continuing with [[Eugene F. Fama]] and [[Kenneth R. French]] in 1992 and 1999,<ref>{{cite web| url=https://ssrn.com/abstract=98678| title=Characteristics, Covariances, and Average Returns: 1929-1997| author1=James L. Davis| author2=Eugene F. Fama| author3=Kenneth R. French| accessdate=June 27, 2025}} Available at SSRN.</ref> academic studies have found that US small cap and US small cap value stocks provided premium returns during the twentieth century. These premium returns were accompanied by greater risk. (See Table 3 and Table 4 below). While US small cap stocks provided a 2% premium return over US large cap stocks over the twentieth century, small cap stocks declined a real -70% over three years during the Great Depression and declined a nominal -90.78% (1929 - 1932) and -53.15% (1972-1974).
{|class=wikitable style="text-align:center" |+ Table 3. Historical returns and risks of U.S. stocks in the 20th century<ref name="Bernstein">{{cite book| author=William Bernstein| author-link=William Bernstein| title=The Four Pillars of Investing| isbn=978-0-07-138529-9}}</ref> !Asset !Annualized return !Worst real three-year loss |- |Large company stocks || 10% || -60% |- |Small company stocks || 12% || -70% |- |}
{|class=wikitable style="text-align:center" width=600px |+ Table 4. Small vs. large, July 1926 - June 2000<ref name="Bernstein" /> !Asset''' !Annualized Return ''' !September 1929 - June 1932 !December 1972 - September 1974 |- |Small Stocks || 12.35% || -90.78% || -53.15% |- |Large Stocks || 10.91% || -84.44% || -43.47% |- |}
In addition to a size premium, twentieth century returns showed the presence of a realized value premium. The 1926 - 2000 return of US small value stocks was 14.87% as compared to the 9.92% return of US small growth stocks.<ref name="Bernstein" /> Figure 1 shows the growth of a dollar investment in each of the four quadrants of market capitalization from 1927 - 2000. For investors to attain these premium returns required long term holding periods, as the market, value, and size factor returns often rotate over time and there are long periods when portfolio [[FAQ small cap funds#What does "tilting" to small mean and how much should I tilt? |tilts]] to small and small value stocks lag the market.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.efficientfrontier.com/ef/700/factors.htm| title=Factor Rotation| publisher=Efficient Frontier| date=2000| accessdate=June 27, 2025}}</ref>
===Prospective risk premium===
The prospective risk premium for small cap and small value stocks is subject to debate. Classic financial theory argues that reliable future premium returns must be based on compensation for risk or there is the possibility that, because the premiums are known, they can be arbitraged away. Behavioral economists<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.quantitativeinvestment.com/documents/common.pdf| title=Commonality In The Determinants Of Expected Stock Returns| author1=Robert A. Haugen| author2=Nardin L. Baker| publisher=Journal of Financial Economics| date=1996| accessdate=June 27, 2025}})</ref> have suggested [[Behavioral pitfalls|behavioral reasons]] for the historical risk premiums.
Others, such as [[John Bogle]], have expressed doubts as to the viability of the small cap and small value premium (see: [[Telltale chart]]):
{{quotation|From 1925 through 1964 - a period of fully 39 years - small caps and large caps provided identical returns. Then, in just four years, through 1968, the small-cap return more than doubled the large-cap return. Virtually that entire margin was lost during the next five years. By 1973, small caps were about at par with large caps for nearly the full half-century. The small caps' reputation was made largely during the 1973-1983 decade.|John Bogle<ref>{{cite book| title=Common Sense on Mutual Funds: Fully Updated 10th Anniversary Edition| publisher=John Wiley & Sons| date=2009| isbn=0-470-13813-0}}</ref>}}
John Bogle also cites the high transaction costs in executing small cap portfolios as a hurdle for realizing small cap premiums. According to Edelen, et.al. US large cap fund have transaction costs (mean 0.77%, median 0.55%); US small cap funds have transaction costs (mean 2.85%, median 2.33%).<ref>{{cite web| url=https://ssrn.com/abstract=951367| title=Scale Effects in Mutual Fund Performance: The Role of Trading Costs| author1=Roger M. Edelen| author2=Richard B. Evans| author3=Gregory B. Kadlec| accessdate=June 27, 2025}} Available at SSRN.</ref>
===International markets===
Research into international stock market performance over the last quarter/half of the twentieth century provided evidence of a realized small cap premium. Hawakini and Keim (2000), in a study of 16 international markets<ref>{{cite web| author1=Gabriel Hawakini| author2=Donald B. Keim| url=http://knowledge.emory.edu/papers/794.pdf| title=The Cross Section of Common Stock Returns: A Review of the Evidence and Some New Findings| publisher=Wharton| date=1999| url-status=dead| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120526072258/http://knowledge.emory.edu/papers/794.pdf| archive-date=May 26, 2012}}</ref> found evidence of a small cap premium in 15 of the 16 countries (the exception being Korea, which provided a monthly -0.40% small cap discount). The positive monthly premium ranged from 0.41% in Singapore to 4.16% in Mexico. The data series in the study varied, with most study periods ending in the 1980s to 1990.
As Dimson, Marsh, and Staunton report, subsequent to the publication of these findings, the small cap premium reversed in international markets during the 1990s.<ref>Dimson, Marsh, and Staunton, ''Triumph of the Optimists:101 Years of Global Investment Returns'', Princeton University Press, 2002. pp.131 -135.</ref> In reference to UK markets, they note:<ref>{{cite web| url=http://faculty-gsb.stanford.edu/nagel/pdfs/UK_VG.pdf| title=Capturing the Value Premium in the UK 1955-2001| date=January 2003| author1=Elroy Dimson| author2=Stefan Nagel| author3=Garrett Quigley| url-status=dead| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060917034510/http://faculty-gsb.stanford.edu/nagel/pdfs/UK_VG.pdf| archive-date=September 6, 2006}}</ref>
{{quotation|Using a new dataset of accounting information merged with share price data we find a strong value premium in the UK for the period 1955-2001. The value premium exists within the small-cap as well as the large-cap universe. We also find that dividend yield as a measure of value produces strikingly similar results. The time-series of return spreads between portfolios sorted according to dividend yields closely matches the results obtained from sorts on book-to-market. However, managers attempting to capture the value premium in the small-cap segment should pay particular attention to rebalancing-induced portfolio turnover and market illiquidity in small-value stocks. Compared to the U.S., the U.K. market for small-cap stocks is relatively illiquid. Trading costs are therefore an even more crucial determinant of overall performance. This is likely to be the case in other non-U.S. markets as well.}}
The 2000s witnessed premium returns for international small cap stocks as evidenced by the performance of MSCI EAFE indexes. Small cap international stocks demonstrated lower correlation to US large (0.72 vs. EAFE 0.86) and US small (0.71 vs. 0.76 EAFE) stocks during the 1999-2008 period.<ref>{{cite web| author1=Gordon Johnson| author2=Shannon Ericson| author3=Vikram Srimurthy| url=http://www.publicpensionsonline.com/public/images/Sml-Cap-Intl-Diversification.pdf| title=Diversification Benefits of International Small-cap Stocks}}{{dead link}}</ref> The case for persistence in lower correlation for small cap international stocks is the tendency for small cap stocks to be economically tied to local national economies as opposed to being global enterprises.
As is true in US markets, international small cap stocks incur higher transaction costs compared to large cap stocks. Quigley provides transaction cost breakdowns for regional markets.
