'''{{PAGENAME}}s''' include all taxable distributions that aren't treated as long-term capital gain.<ref group="note"> The instructions for [https://www.irs.gov/instructions/i1099div/ar01.html#d0e329 Box 1a, IRS Form 1099-DIV] state: ''Enter dividends, including dividends from money market funds, net short-term capital gains from mutual funds, and other distributions on stock. Include reinvested dividends and section 404(k) dividends paid directly from the corporation. Include as a dividend the amount of the recipient's share of investment expenses that you report in box 5.'' </ref> Ordinary dividends can be either [[Qualified dividend | qualified dividends]], taxed at preferential capital gains rates, or [[Non-qualified dividends | non-qualified dividends]] which are taxed at income tax rates.

